<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Teremar at December 28, 2004 03:17 PM</strong></p>
<p>OoW was a huge improvement over PoP or GoD for non-raiders like me, no doubt about that. I would quibble about some things, like the runes, or the way Dragorns and Muramites coexist peacefully and even assist each other in fighting adventurers. But those are quibbles.</p>

<p>The core problem is the fights themselves. OoW continues and reaffirms a trend that started in the high end of Velious, became universal in PoP, was reversed in LDoN (except in 65 hards) and returned with a vengeance in GoD. Namely, the main paradigm for combat is fighting one high-DPS mob at a time. Anything but "slowed mob beats on tank, healer heals tank, everyone else does damage" has a very significant risk of death or even wiping the group. Adds are a particular emergency, and thus the zones are designed such that they are very rare.</p>

<p>The trouble is, it's a pretty boring paradigm. The healer is really the only one that has to pay too much attention. For the slower and DPS classes the only challenge is seeing how early you can do your thing without getting aggro--once you realize the group's really better off if you don't push your luck, interest wanes rapidly.</p>

<p>I think there's a reason both EQ2 and WoW say right up front that the game is designed around many vs. many fights. They're inherently more complex (and thus to me more interesting). I'm not sure EQ would be wise to try to change course and imitate them--the people who are sticking with EQ at this point are most likely happy with the current paradigm. But it's the main reason I switched to WoW.</p>
