<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Redcloud at December 29, 2004 05:03 AM</strong></p>
<p>To me there are two different issues on omens runes.</p>

<p>The first is that too many are needed per level. The second that there are so many needed that you are bound to buy some or need to be bored into fighting zones aimed at lower levels. Both are unfun and unneeded. They don't add longevity to expansion, they just put off people that have gapping holes in their spell books. It seems a good idea tha has gone wrong. If they wanted to do something like that, they'd probably need to have random trash drop level 66-69 runes in MPG and RS like Sol Ro dropped lower level ones. That's 101 gamers psychology all over again: don't force people to do content below their intented level of play, be it in group or raid.</p>

<p>Regarding fighting in Omens: I agree it's "pull one, kill one" or "pull 4, CR for the next 30 minutes". Sebilis was fun because there were a great many mobs to mez, root, snare, charm, off tank, whatever with mobs gating that could or could not wipe the group. Today a gating mob in group bringing 3 friends is usually a disaster.</p>

<p>The pulling and CC aspect of EQ seem pretty watered down. It's quite a loss in excitement for a great many people out there. Not just those who perform those tasks but for everyone wishing to do more dangerous things than sitting hours on end killing single pulled statics.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;loral&#64;loralciriclight&#46;com">Loral</a> at December 29, 2004 08:34 AM</strong></p>
<p>I certainly would like to see more encounter variance including many-on-many and other forms of battles to defeat beasts.  With instanced zones, expeditions, adventures and the capability for timed tasks, SOE has a lot more control over encounters.  I was disappointed with the Hollows expeditions considering how much potential they had to tune and taylor encounters around the groups that entered.</p>

<p>The MPG trials and the Justice trials are examples of battles in instanced encounters that offer different forms of battles and different solutions.  Justice failed because it was never really instanced and it became a bottleneck for forward progression, that is never good.</p>

<p>Players are often smart enough to figure out new ways to battle.  Remember how cool your first AE group was?  They could set up instanced encounters that give any group that same feeling of being swarmed with mobs.</p>

<p>Most of Omens up until the MPG trials seems to follow the same combat path of previous expansions: camp in a spot, pull single mobs, cheer when a named mob shows up.  I would like to have seen more MPG like encounters earlier in the expansion.</p>

<p>Spell runes dropped to 20k on Quellious.  After about three months of hunting I have nearly all of my minor runes, I have all six lesser runes, and about four normal runes.  I only have one 69 rune but I have yet to step into Riftseekers.  I would like to have seen either a merchant or a quest that offers you one or two runes per level up front to at least get you started and reduce the amount you have to loot or buy.  For the most part it is a better system than both PoP and GoD however, but one not as consistant as LDON.</p>
