<p>I liked the original vision of ancient spells (though I never saw one): better versions of the spells everyone has.</p>

<p>I'd be happy with a three tier system for class-defining spells. First there would be a vendor-sold version, then a better version that dropped from single-group mobs, then an ancient version that dropped from raid mobs. The differences shouldn't be too big, but any improvement in spells will motivate casters without having to cripple those who haven't gotten runes to drop.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Horzek at December 30, 2004 02:52 PM</strong></p>
<p>Once again I return to read and learn from my favorite EQ site.  It is always an enlightening experience.  I would like to make a few comments based on some of what I have read today.</p>

<p>Clerics and Invisibility:  I play a cleric and have had a great deal of trouble getting into zones and even to camps.  My solution was to buy a pack full of invis potions and hope I was handy enough with their use to be able to live and arrive at my destination.  Now that the cash drain on clerics via peridots has been lifted I dont mind the Invis potions quite so much.  The one thing I would like to see for them is stackability.  With so many items being stackable I see no good reason why I should not be able to stack invis potions instead of taking up half my inventory.</p>

<p>Runes:  This has become a very sore spot for me.  I hate camping for runes.  Being a cleric in a zone where the runes drops means I dare not blink for hours on end because as sure as I sit here, during that moment I blink something bad will happen that I will miss the opportunity to get a heal off in time for.  After intense concentration for hours, a rune drops and because the things are worth 20k or more in the bazaar the warriors and rangers and everyone else is rolling on them.  I dont expect special treatment on runes, just fair treatment.  I sure dont have the hundreds of thousands of pp that it would take to get all my spells up to date.  </p>

<p>Rune camping is not fun.  It is especially not fun for clerics.  I would like to see at least the major class spells made available much easier.  If there must be bazaar spells, they should be the spells in the " sure would be nice " category.  Improved heals, major buffs do not count in this line.  Let me roll for runes that will allow me to perform some special holy rite on a tradeskill item that can then be turned around for another to benefit as well.</p>

<p>I should never have purchased WoW.  It truly has killed what ever desire I had left for EQ.  In the past month I have logged in twice and both times for under 10 minutes.  I checked the rune prices in the bazaar and they were still rediculously high.  I refuse to continue to play that way.</p>

<p>For me EQ is simply not fun anymore.  The one truly outstanding feature of EQ was the ability of a small 6 person group to get together and enjoy each others company.  I have not found the same group spirit in any other on line game I have tried.  Somehow they really got it right.  </p>

<p>There is to my way of thinking one fatal flaw in EQ.  In my view, the Named Drops is killing the game fun.  I dont mind having named drops but the game needs balance on mob drops.  There should be a chance of a decent drop from any mob you kill in any zone you go to.  The drop should be somewhat level based and should be random enough to prevent farming.  I think EQ2 is getting this to some extend and WoW seems to have it right as well.</p>

<p>One final point is questing.  With EQ questing for the most part seems to be mind numbing and tedious.  I have not forgotten the month I spent getting enough faction so I could continue a quest I had gotten.  Having to kill 1000 green con mobs was and remains boring and basically a giant waste of time.  It is like going to the barber for a hair cut and being told that you can get your hair cut but you must remain in the chair until your hair grows another half inch before he can proceed.</p>
